class Solution {
    public String answerString(String word, int numFriends) {
        String maxStr = word.substring(0, word.length() - numFriends + 1);
        for (int i = 1; i < numFriends; i++) {
            maxStr = maxStr.compareTo(word.substring(i, word.length() - numFriends + i + 1)) > 0 ? maxStr : word.substring(i, word.length() - numFriends + i + 1);
        }
        return maxStr;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution directly compares the lexicographically largest possible substrings by iterating through the word and comparing substrings of the same length. It keeps track of the maximum string found so far. The key strength is its linear time complexity, making it efficient for large inputs. 
